<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Sphaeralcea ambigua </i> is is a short-lived (<15 years), drought-deciduous, perennial subshrub that is common in the Mojave, Colorado and Sonoran deserts. Infraspecific varieties vary in flower color from orange to pink. The species is insect pollinated, and its seeds are dispersed short distances by rodents or ants (DeFalco et al. 2009). <i>S. ambigua </i>  is an early seral species that occurs commonly after disturbance such as fire (Abella 2010, Evens et al. 2014, Shryock et al. 2014), and it consistently flowers from year to year to develop a seedbank, despite fluctuations in precipitation (Beatley 1974).<br/>
<br/>
Stands of this alliance are variable depending on rainfall, time since disturbance, and other seasonal site conditions. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
