<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">This early seral alliance replaces longer-lived desert plant communities, especially in post-fire settings. <i>Sphaeralcea ambigua </i>and various other native desert herbs, including <i>Salvia columbariae, </i>readily germinate after disturbance including fire, and interannual cover varies depending on moisture availability. Burned sites often host an abundance of these forbs and other herbaceous species, such as <i>Achatherum speciosum, Bromus rubens, Eriogonum </i>spp., and <i>Erodium cicutarium, </i>as well as short-lived shrubs such as <i>Gutierrezia microcephala </i>and <i>G. sarothrae </i>(Abella 2010, Evens et al. 2014, Shryock et al. 2014). Within decades, longer-lived types will regain dominance, though multi-decadal intervals (>50 years) are best for recovery.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
