    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p><i>Sphaeralcea ambigua </i>is wide-ranging in the warm deserts of California, including the Sonoran and Colorado deserts (322B and 322C), and desert slopes of Southern California (M262Bp) where stands have not been sampled but are likely to occur in post-burn or other disturbance settings.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Aj, Al). Stands have been sampled in the Black Mountains, Mid Hills, Piute Range, and near the Cinder Cones Lava Bed and Shadow Valley (Evens et al. 2014), though they are likely more common across the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Ff). Stands occur on valley floors and slopes of the Panamint Range (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Sphaeralcea ambigua </i> is a preferred species for post-fire plant restoration. Colonization of burned areas by <i>Sphaeralcea ambigua </i>supports use of desert habitats by the Mojave Desert tortoise (<i>Gopherus agassizii</i>), a threatened species (Drake et al. 2015). These stands can naturally transition to shrub and tree stands within 10-50+ years after disturbance, though invasion by non-native grasses, including <i>Bromus rubens, </i>can increase fuels and fire threat. </div>
</div>

    

    

